{{Orphan|date=March 2017}}

'''Xenointoxication''' is a form of [[pest control]] in which an [[ectoparasite]]'s [[host animal]] is dosed with a substance that is poisonous to the parasite. When the parasite feeds on its host, it is poisoned, and eventually dies.

An example of this strategy is the experimental use of oral [[ivermectin]] in humans to kill [[Bed bug (insect)|bed bug]]s and [[parasitic worm]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pill Could Join Arsenal Against Bedbugs |url=http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/12/31/pill-could-join-arsenal-against-bedbugs/ |work=The New York Times |accessdate=1 January 2013 |author=Donald G. McNeil Jr. |date=December 31, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Donald G. McNeil Jr. |title=Pet pill could join arsenal against bedbugs |url=http://www.statesman.com/news/news/pet-pill-could-join-arsenal-against-bedbugs/nWMwd/?goback=%2Egmp_3774139%2Egde_3774139_member_215260298 |date=February 16, 2013 |work=Statesmen |accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref>  This technique has also been used to combat other ectoparasites.<ref>{{cite web|title=How To Protect from Bed Bugs|url=http://www.bedbugguide.com/home-remedies-for-bed-bugs-and-how-to-protect-your-home/|website=Bed Bug Guide|accessdate=13 March 2014|author=Tonya W. Padron|date=May 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.jfponline.com/pages.asp?id=10564 |title=When bed bugs bite |author=Mark K. Huntington |journal=Journal of Family Practice |date=July 2012 |volume=61 |issue=7 |pages=384–388 |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205061216/http://www.jfponline.com/pages.asp?id=10564 |archive-date=2012-12-05}}</ref>

This method was unsuccessful in a 1969 study attempting to control ''[[Triatoma infestans]]'' in chicken houses because even though some bugs that fed on the treated birds did die, so did the birds, and the birds that survived produced fewer eggs.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Marsden |first1=P. D. |title=Xeno-intoxication in the control of Triatomidae |journal=Arch. Fac. Hig. Saude Publ. Univ. S. Paulo |date=1969 |volume=34 |issue=119/120 |pages=25–42 |url=https://www.cabdirect.org/cabdirect/abstract/19702902765 |accessdate=22 March 2017}}</ref>

